07425nam a22007935i 9780520919266DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19991999cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209192667 a10.1525/97805209192662doi  a(DE-B1597)648671  a(OCoLC)1419790547  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aSOC0020002bisacsh1 aScheper-Hughes/Sargent, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSmall Wars :bThe Cultural Politics of Childhood /cScheper-Hughes/Sargent; ed. by Nancy Scheper-Hughes, Carolyn Fishel Sargent. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[1999] 4c©1999  a1 online resource (464 p.) :b20 black-and-white photos, 20 tables, 1 line drawing.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: The Cultural Politics of Childhood -- tPART I. Negotiating Parenthood and Childhood -- tInfanticide, the Spirits of Aborted Fetuses, and the Making of Motherhood in Japan -- tAmbiguities Lost Fashioning the Fetus into a Child in Ecuador and the United States -- tReproductive Partners Doctor-Woman Relations in Israeli and Canadian IVF Contexts -- tExamining Surrogacy Discourses Between Feminine Power and Exploitation -- tNeonatal Jaundice The Cultural History of the Creation and Maintenance of a "Disease" of Newborns -- tMamitis and the Traumas of Development in a Colonia Popular of Mexico City -- tEthical Reflections: Taking a Walk on the Wild Side -- tPART II: The Cultural Politics of Child Survival -- tHistorical Perspectives on Infant and Child Mortality in Northwestern Portugal -- tChildren's Health as Accumulated Capital Structural Adjustment in the Dominican Republic and Cuba -- tBad Boys and Good Girls: The Implications of Gender Ideology for Child Health in Jamaica -- tWho Is the Rogue? Hunger, Death, and Circumstance in John Mampe Square -- tPart III: Small Wars: Children and Violence -- t"Good Mothers," "Babykillers," and Fatal Child Maltreatment -- tRitual and Satanic Abuse in England -- tInstitutionalized Sex Abuse and the Catholic Church -- tChildren in Extremely Difficult Circumstances War and Its Aftermath in Croatia -- tFamilies and Children in Pain in the U.S. Inner City -- tBrazilian Apartheid: Street Kids and the Struggle for Urban Space -- tNothing Bad Intended: Child Discipline, Punishment, and Survival in a Shanty town in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil -- tNOTES ON CONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSmall Wars gathers together a hard-hitting series of essays that demonstrate how, at the close of the twentieth century, the world's children are affected by global political-economic structures and by everyday practices embedded in the micro-level interactions of local cultures. Perceived as avenging spirits of aborted fetuses in Japan; as obstacles to, or desired commodities of, narcissistic adult fulfillment in North America; as foot soldiers cast onto the paths of drug wars in Spanish Harlem and ethnic wars in the former Yugoslavia; and as "street kids" and public enemies of the middle classes in Brazil, children—these authors suggest—are losing ground. The modern conception of the child as vulnerable and needing protection is giving way to that of the child as miniature adult, a full-circle return to Philippe Ariès's notion of premodern childhood.The authors raise vital questions about social and structural violence and its impact on children and families; about policies that portray children as innocent victims on the one hand and as irredeemable criminals on the other; and about the global economic and political conditions that place many of the world's children at risk. Providing groundbreaking contributions to the contemporary social history and ethnography of childhood, this volume will be important to readers across the social sciences.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aAnthropology. 4aGeneral. 4aSocial Science. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh1 aBirenbaum-Carmeli, Daphna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBourgois, Philippe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrett, John A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrettell, Caroline B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFishel Sargent, Carolyn , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGoldstein, Donna M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGutmann, Matthew C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarris, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoffman, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKorbin, Jill E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLa Fontaine, J. S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLerer, Leonard B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorgan, Lynn M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNiermeyer, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOlujic, Maria B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPicone, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoberts, Elizabeth F. S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSargent, Carolyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScheper-Hughes, Nancy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScheper-Hughes, Nancy, eeditor.4edt4http://i